Conclusion from the graph:¶

  • Better "bins" are shown in the "red" part.
  • Bins within 350000 to 550000 are more likely to have higher approval rates, this result agree with our plot from R.
  • Bins with high "retry" attempts will more likely to have lower approval rates.

From this plot we know the overall distribution of the data. Next, we can try some clustering methods that can hopefully generate a more accurate way to seperate the "red" part.

# X is the feature variables that contains 'bin' and 'retry_indicator' columns.
# To make classification, change 'M0_Approval%' to 0 or 1 with specific threshold.
feature_cols = ['bin', 'retry_indicator'] 
X = data1[feature_cols].astype(object)

### Threshold can be changed here ###
threshold = 0.5
approval_indicator = np.where(data1['M0_Approval%'] > threshold, 1, 0)
data1['Approval_indicator'] = approval_indicator


Y = data1.Approval_indicator

# Split dataset into 70% training and 30% test
X_train, X_test, Y_train, Y_test = train_test_split(X, Y, test_size=0.3, random_state=1)

The following cell displays a decision tree after pruning.

Note: The full decision tree is too large to be performed by my PC. Therefore, I used Google Colab to generate the full tree, as shown in the file "Full_tree.png".

# Decision tree with pruning.

clf = tree.DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth = 5)
clf.fit(X_train, Y_train)

graph = Source(tree.export_graphviz(clf, out_file=None, feature_names=X.columns, class_names=['0', '1'], filled=True))
graph.format = 'png'
graph.render('Pruned',view = True)

# Display the tree
IPdisplay.Image('Pruned.png')

In [107]:
# Predict the response for test dataset
Y_pred = clf.predict(X_test)
print("Accuracy:",round(metrics.accuracy_score(Y_test, Y_pred) * 100, 2), "%")

Accuracy: 80.96 %

Conclusion: A simply decision tree with 5 layers can achieve about 81% accuracy.¶

Next, lets try to find a better model without overfitting.

In [108]:
optimal_depth = []
tree_accuracy = []
for depth in range(1, 100):
    optimal_depth.append(depth)
    clf = tree.DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth = depth)
    clf.fit(X_train, Y_train)
    Y_pred = clf.predict(X_test)
    tree_accuracy.append(metrics.accuracy_score(Y_test, Y_pred))


print("Optimal depth:", optimal_depth[tree_accuracy.index(max(tree_accuracy))])
print("Accuracy:", round(max(tree_accuracy)*100, 2), "%")

Optimal depth: 16
Accuracy: 83.97 %

Conclusion: depth = 16 decision tree gives us a more accurate prediction, with 83.98% accuracy.¶

Note: Other optionals like criterion="entropy" etc. may improve the accuracy as well.

For example, change the line to:

clf = tree.DecisionTreeClassifier(criterion="entropy", max_depth = depth)

Since the idea is similar, we won't repeat in here.
